; font-size:11pt">would </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">undermine the intention to ensure that removals of families with children are conducted in accordance with the law.</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> residence test would also be unworkable:</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Lawful residence is a complex area of immigration law and it is clear that many legal practitioners who do not specialise in this area would be unable accurately </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">assess eligibility for the purposes of advising </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">in relation to other areas of law including entitlements to essential services.  It is highly likely, therefore, that survivors of torture who do meet the requirements of the residence test would </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">still </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">face difficulty accessing legal services.</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; m